    <h1>All Dining Halls</h1>
    {sampleData.map((d) => (
      <DiningHallCard key={d.id} {...d} />
    ))}
  </div>
);
```

In this code, the dot (`...`) before the `d` parameter in the `DiningHallCard` component is invalid syntax and should be replaced with a spread operator (`...`) to pass the properties of the `d` object as props to the `DiningHallCard` component: 

```
<DiningHallCard key={d.id} {...d} />
``` 

The fixed code above should resolve the syntax error.

This error might have occurred due to incorrect imports or missing declarations. Here's the fixed syntax, which includes the necessary import statement:

```
import React from 'react';
import DiningHallCard from './DiningHallCard';
import { SampleDataType } from '../types/types';

interface Props {
  data: SampleDataType[];
}

const DiningHallList: React.FC<Props> = ({ data }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>All Dining Halls</h1>
      {data.map((d) => (
        <DiningHallCard key={d.id} {...d} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

export default DiningHallList;
```

In this case, the "div" error message appeared because the React module wasn't imported at the top of the file. The `import React from 'react'` statement has been added at the top to fix the error.

Also, make sure to check if the `SampleDataType` type is properly declared, imported, and used in your code.
